snippet.textDisplay: It's an illusion and they guide your thinking through frame-dropping technique in video. When it says "horizontal axis", video is reset to start from plausible frame to support horizontal axis motion illusion. When it says "vertical axis", the video is reset again. Without these "resets" (frame drops), it'd be extremely hard to switch your reference of perception.

snippet.textDisplay: That is so interesting. Essentially, it's taking advantage of the problem of projections. The catch is, the object isn't really rotating at all. It's only when shadows or corners are emphasized that our brains then pick a branch of the projection's preimage that takes us back to three-dimensional space. But there are many such branches (i.e. many such ways to go back to three dimensions).
